A team of Czech and German scientists test new combinations that can slow the proliferation of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed a drug immunity.
This reality takes, in some cases, the top on the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on the common variants of the virus as well as some medications already available.
There is no way to cure AIDS at this time.
However, the life of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of medications that prevent the multiplication of HIV in the body.
Their consumption, however, leads to a number of side effects.
Furthermore, the repression of this multiplication has the effect on the development of what is called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are an assembly of bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way than all the drugs used so far and that’s why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new “upgrade” substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their connections to the viral proteins.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages are formed by the bore, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a HIV virus protein that is essential for the virus’s life cycle.
