The United Nations Group has plans for emission reduction
The UN-sponsored climate conference – characterized so far by unorganized assignments and mutual punishments – has come back under the fire of the ramp on Friday, due to the publication of a document highlighting the ambitious reductions of greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations taking most of the burden, in the near future.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as long as it cleared the way to take.
But it has been seen as a significant advance in the short-time negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from all over the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Written by a special UN working group, the text does not say how much wealthy countries would give the poor to support the climate warming, ongoing and long-term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could decrease their carbon production and what would be the upper boundary of the global temperature rise that the leaders would be willing to tolerate.
It gives a great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what United Nations Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the complete image".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 percent compared to the levels of 1990, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also resumed negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change — to resist floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, U.S. Representative for Climate Negotiation rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if these were not funded by developed countries.
This change is a sign that the Obama administration becomes harder to China than the Bush administration was, two years ago.
The U.S. will not sign an agreement without efforts and actions of the leading developing countries, Stern said who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be checked by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Foreign Minister He Yafei said the main U.S. negotiator was either missing "good sense" or "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not finance China to fight climate warming.
With the future economic trajectoes of the world’s leading powers on the game, defects have appeared both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about the saving of individual economies than the saving of the planet, with China and the United States struggling on their respective obligations while the poorest nations insist on the fact that the two dozen of the most influential countries ignore the scientific imperative to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rica delegate, said it was not surprising that major powers are struggling to know who should suffer the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even if vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make major emitters responsible for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to put pressure to get a legally binding treaty, in Copenhagen, although most major participants say that negotiations will lead at least, to a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Insular States, which brings together 43 members, has drawn up a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the Climate Unit of the European Commission, said that the action of the small island states has "placed a political pressure on the comprehensive political process", in part by what they are now united and they ask emerging economies such as China and India, to act.
Debates have become an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most problems in instance before the heads of governments reach an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Environment Minister, Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice-Ministry have descended from their airplane and jumped into the Bella Center building to attend closed-door meetings and news conferences, so that they can make complaints that will be examined during the next week.
