Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the major French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will be vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, reminds the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about bringing employees to "values" determined from above as it was before, imposing consumers the products thought by the factory technicians.
By putting the customer in the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets in place... although the authority’s temptation to impose products unconnected to the customer’s preference factors returns regularly!
A demobilization of employees can lead to a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects mainly the cadres.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IEA “requires from all stakeholders a proactive approach and a prospective vision”; it requires from employees a commitment that the revenue of authority management contradicts entirely.
That’s why we call for a managerial revolution that would consist in placing employees at the center of the company’s concerns as the customer.
Relative Use of Internal Opinion Surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – stimulate this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately I am afraid that not.
First, because I could see that, faced with a new situation, every structure eventually succeeds, after a lot of turns, to do priority... what she has always done.
Then, because authority – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic vision of human behavior.
Out of the major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "neurosciences" and widely spread, unknown to them, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, suggesting that it is possible to handle the “leviers” (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent Ipsos investigation published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unadapted to the world of today.
Identification and measurement of mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental conclusion: for employees, the commitment to the company is possible only if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this design of employees’ motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business on the basis of a predefined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their management of human resources “to the place”.
They thus create a favorable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
