Turkish justice dissolves pro-Kurd party, heavy decision of consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday the dissolution of the country’s leading pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by anger demonstrations in the Kurdish community, in the southeastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision risks to greatly complicate the government’s task, which has just stretched the hand to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "foyer of activities that are harmful to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the Court Hasim Kiliç told the press, after four days of discussions.
The decision was made unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to resolve the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including his president Ahmet Türk and deputy Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the withdrawal of the parliamentary immunity of Mr. Türk and Mr. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party’s property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (from 550).
His leaders had warned before the verdict that the MPs would leave the Parliament rather than sitting as parliamentarians without label.
The decision follows a procedure launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political vitrine of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, assures that it has “no organic ties” with the PKK but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s ruling comes as the government has just stretched the hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen its rights, to try to cut off the Kurdish support to the PKK and end the conflict.
The DTP leaders had said a dissolution could lead to a recurrence of tensions in the southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
As soon as justice announced, a thousand protesters gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large south-eastern city populated mostly by Kurds.
Police shot lacrymogenic grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw molotov cocktails or stones, with fronts.
A hundred people also protested in Istanbul.
