The Birth of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae was similar to the other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped measureed about 2 meters long to 1.50 meters high, its rear limbs were powerful, its lengthy neck was equipped with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with scratches and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to have these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico which was at the time part of the emerging land of the supercontinent, the Pangée and was located to the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa illuminates a new day the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
In fact, it informs us about the relativity links, the distribution and the characteristics of these.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertaken excavations in the company of other paleontologists, on the site of Gohst Ranch north of New Mexico.
Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the exploration team tells that they sometimes find a dozen bones in a day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The findings have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers baptized it with the name of Tawa according to the word of the Indians Hopi for the god of the sun.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a very exceptional discovery: the dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to some fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all experts in paleontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander from the University of Bonn does not find that this discovery is spectacular, but he says it allows to confirm some theories about the beginnings of the evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropodes (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaur and the biociraptor later appeared and from which the birds descend, the sauropodes, the quadrupedes at the long neck, and those that are related to them and the ornithischian herbivores of which the species such as the triceratops and the stégosars are part of.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting ratio of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae possessed small air bags in its bones at the scalp, as well as the birds who are the descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in Tawa hallae, the vertebrates were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in its bones.
Since the related line of the enormous sauropods also had air bags and a light bone, it can be thought that their common ancestor had already this beneficial innovation.
Three consecutive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Saurians appeared there.
Thus, the three major lines of evolution divided and distributed from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. all the emerging lands that formed the supercontinent Pangée.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers advance.
Alan Turner from the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of the Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
Of course there are some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn says there is an even older species, the silesaure, who lived in today’s Poland and belongs to a group related to the dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view as there is a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while practically no of them is found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs have succeeded in becoming the dominant tetrapods of the secondary age when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and with many other Saurians.
At the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet, thus promoting the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such a success is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There could have been a mass extinction to which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or then, the dinosaurs were better adapted and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
However, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favoured the prosperity of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and that since then was growing in the shadow: it was mammals.
