75% of working mothers have had professional problems due to their maternity
Work discrimination has increased over the past few years, especially for women from young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what reveals the study “Fecondity and professional career of women in Spain”, conducted by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institut de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, does not leave place to doubt: 75% of the working mothers saw their career limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of a couple life and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get in couple earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, decline entering a couple life and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after having settled into a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 in those working in the public sector. “These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to reject the union and arrival of children.
Moreover, the type of employment exercised largely affects maternity, but less the date of beginning of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that grows the age gap between women’s marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they marry and have their first child later.
The difference remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who took primary and higher studies respectively were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and at 32.1 years in average.
"A further discretion appears also among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have undergone basic studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have undergone middle or higher level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a pre-condition for marriage and the arrival of a child,” said Delgado.
