Emergency removal is now mandatory.
As this happened with the ABS brake anti-blocking system and as it will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency brake assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are also already mandatory on newly registered tourist and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a short period has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, by its way of action, it can also contribute to the avoidance of many back shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's footstep.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken advantage of all its strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the contrary, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to a EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided every year.
