In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a crash are returned to a garage, where an expert has to assess the damages suffered and the cost of the repair.
Each disaster is different, and the calculation of the cost of the pieces and the working time can constitute a long and complex work.
Manual calculation of the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including pieces and workforce can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of experts use this type of systems.
The service providers and solutions for accident assessment and maintenance are dedicated to the collection of the information provided by the manufacturers, and then process them and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other competing companies in the field of industry assessment and information development tools are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by manufacturers is far from being simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so that over the last five years, more versions, variants and motorizations have been launched than over the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes to the market, these companies begin to work.
This is a very hard work, because it is necessary to catalog each of the thousand pieces of the vehicle and register its price.
In addition, a “smart” graphic image of each model is set on which you can click on the different parts of a tourist car.
If it’s a massively sold model, the work can be ready within a week if the process advances very quickly.
If it’s a low-selling car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information about 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have, for example, information about the Porsche, but not the Ferrari or the Lamborghini.
For vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centers worldwide (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them is specialized in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million per year in the development of these databases.
Each month, 2.5 million data is recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer different products.
The most common application concerns repair and maintenance, but depending on the countries, there are also tools for managing the breakdowns or for calculating the venal or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
